1
00:01:08,400 --> 00:01:12,700
You will travel far, my little Kal-El.

2
00:01:13,300 --> 00:01:15,300
But we will never leave you...

3
00:01:15,800 --> 00:01:18,300
...even in the face of our deaths.

4
00:01:19,500 --> 00:01:21,900
You will make my strength your own.

5
00:01:23,200 --> 00:01:26,400
You will see my life through your eyes...

6
00:01:27,300 --> 00:01:30,000
...as your life will be seen through mine.

7
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:37,100
The son becomes the father,
and the father the son.

8
00:04:54,300 --> 00:04:56,700
In spite of your past...

9
00:04:58,900 --> 00:05:01,500
...I know you're a good man.

10
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:04,700
And all good men...

11
00:05:05,200 --> 00:05:07,600
...deserve a second chance.

12
00:05:15,300 --> 00:05:18,300
From the moment
I received your first letter...

13
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:21,200
...I knew you were not like the rest.

14
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:26,400
You came from nothing...

15
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,700
...and you worked so hard
to get where you are.

16
00:05:30,600 --> 00:05:33,400
You might have made a few mistakes.

17
00:05:33,700 --> 00:05:36,400
- Gertrude, for God's sake!
- Damn it, Gertrude, let us in now!

18
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:42,000
You said that if I helped you
get out of prison...

19
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:45,500
...you'd take care of me.

20
00:05:46,400 --> 00:05:48,500
And you have.

21
00:05:49,800 --> 00:05:53,900
You've shown me pleasures
that I've never known.

22
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:57,600
That's why you deserve...

23
00:05:57,800 --> 00:05:59,600
...everything.

24
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:04,400
I love you...

25
00:06:04,900 --> 00:06:06,900
...Lex Luthor.

26
00:06:22,400 --> 00:06:24,800
Gertrude, let us in. He's a crook.

27
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:26,900
He doesn't love you, Gertrude!

28
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:28,400
He's a monster! Gertrude!

29
00:06:45,400 --> 00:06:47,500
- You can keep that.
- Oh, God.

30
00:06:47,600 --> 00:06:48,900
The rest is mine.

31
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,700
We're done.

32
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:27,100
Bye, Martha.

33
00:09:57,500 --> 00:09:59,500
Oh, Clark.

34
00:10:02,300 --> 00:10:05,000
Oh, my boy.

35
00:10:51,100 --> 00:10:53,600
Will you get that thing out of my face!

36
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:01,900
Lex, your friends give me the creeps.

37
00:11:02,100 --> 00:11:03,900
Prison is a creepy place, Kitty.

38
00:11:04,100 --> 00:11:06,400
One needs to make creepy friends
in order to survive.

39
00:11:06,600 --> 00:11:09,000
Even a man with my vast talents
is worth less inside...

40
00:11:09,200 --> 00:11:12,900
...than a carton of cigarettes and
a sharp piece of metal in your pocket.

41
00:11:16,400 --> 00:11:19,400
Do you know the story of Prometheus?
No, of course you don't.

42
00:11:19,600 --> 00:11:23,500
Prometheus was a god who stole
the power of fire from the other gods...

43
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:25,300
...and gave control of it to mortals.

44
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:28,000
In essence, he gave us technology.
He gave us power.

45
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:31,600
So we're stealing fire? In the Arctic.

46
00:11:31,800 --> 00:11:35,200
Actually, sort of. You see, whoever
controls technology controls the world.

47
00:11:35,400 --> 00:11:38,000
The Roman Empire ruled the world
because they built roads.

48
00:11:38,100 --> 00:11:40,900
The British Empire ruled the world
because they built ships.

49
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:44,500
America, the atom bomb,
and so on and so forth.

50
00:11:44,600 --> 00:11:46,200
I just want what Prometheus wanted.

51
00:11:46,600 --> 00:11:50,100
Sounds great, Lex, but you're not a god.

52
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,900
Gods are selfish beings
who fly around in little red capes...

53
00:11:56,100 --> 00:11:58,300
...and don't share their power
with mankind.

54
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:00,000
Hey, boss.

55
00:12:00,600 --> 00:12:02,200
We found something.

56
00:12:06,900 --> 00:12:09,500
No, I don't wanna be a god.

57
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:12,600
I just wanna bring fire to the people.

58
00:12:13,600 --> 00:12:17,100
And I want my cut.

59
00:12:58,100 --> 00:13:00,300
Was this his house?

60
00:13:01,100 --> 00:13:03,600
You might think so. Most would.

61
00:13:03,800 --> 00:13:06,700
This is more of a monument
to a long dead...

62
00:13:06,800 --> 00:13:09,300
...and extremely powerful civilization.

63
00:13:09,500 --> 00:13:12,000
This is where he learned who he was.

64
00:13:12,500 --> 00:13:15,100
This is where he came for guidance.

65
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:27,500
Possibilities.

66
00:13:27,700 --> 00:13:31,600
Endless possibilities.

67
00:14:14,700 --> 00:14:17,600
You act like you've been here before.

68
00:14:42,600 --> 00:14:44,300
My son...

69
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:49,100
...you do not remember me.

70
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,000
I am Jor-El.

71
00:14:52,400 --> 00:14:54,400
I'm your father.

72
00:14:54,600 --> 00:14:58,500
By now, I will have been dead
many thousands of your years.

73
00:14:58,700 --> 00:15:02,000
- He thinks I'm his son.
- You are the only survivor of Krypton.

74
00:15:02,600 --> 00:15:07,600
Embedded in the crystals before you is
the total accumulation of all literature...

75
00:15:07,800 --> 00:15:10,500
...and scientific fact
from dozens of other worlds...

76
00:15:10,700 --> 00:15:14,000
...spanning the 28 known galaxies.

77
00:15:14,500 --> 00:15:16,800
There are questions to be asked.

78
00:15:17,400 --> 00:15:19,000
Here in this...

79
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:21,600
This Fortress of Solitude...

80
00:15:22,100 --> 00:15:25,500
...we shall try to find
the answers together.

81
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:27,100
Can he see us?

82
00:15:27,800 --> 00:15:29,400
No, he's dead.

83
00:15:30,500 --> 00:15:31,800
So, my son...

84
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:37,000
...Kal-El...

85
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:42,300
...speak.

86
00:15:43,900 --> 00:15:45,800
Tell me everything...

87
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:48,500
...starting with crystals.

88
00:18:38,100 --> 00:18:39,500
Hey, boy.

89
00:19:04,500 --> 00:19:06,400
- on Tuesday, between support...

90
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:08,800
- hindered the firefighting efforts
for all those...

91
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:13,500
Police have finally arrived and it's
still complete mayhem down here.

92
00:19:14,800 --> 00:19:17,100
Fighting broke out in the
southernmost region...

93
00:19:17,200 --> 00:19:19,500
...with border fire
and small-arms attacks prevalent.

94
00:19:19,700 --> 00:19:21,400
Don't worry, I buried it this morning.

95
00:19:21,600 --> 00:19:24,500
- it was futile trying to force him
to testify before a grand jury.

96
00:19:24,700 --> 00:19:26,100
Mom?

97
00:19:27,500 --> 00:19:29,400
Five years.

98
00:19:31,200 --> 00:19:34,500
If your father was alive,
he never would have let you go.

99
00:19:35,200 --> 00:19:36,700
I almost gave up hope.

100
00:19:36,800 --> 00:19:40,000
I just thought
I would never see you again.

101
00:19:40,700 --> 00:19:43,100
Oh, Clark.

102
00:19:50,100 --> 00:19:52,700
Did you find what you were looking for?

103
00:19:53,500 --> 00:19:57,000
I thought, hoped...

104
00:19:57,800 --> 00:19:59,600
...it might still be there.

105
00:20:00,200 --> 00:20:02,000
Your home?

106
00:20:04,400 --> 00:20:06,600
That place was a graveyard.

107
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:09,400
I'm all that's left.

108
00:20:11,600 --> 00:20:14,900
Clark, the universe is a big place.

109
00:20:15,500 --> 00:20:17,600
And you don't know who's out there.

110
00:20:19,400 --> 00:20:21,700
And even if you are the last...

111
00:20:24,200 --> 00:20:25,900
...you're not alone.

112
00:20:30,600 --> 00:20:32,100
I know.

113
00:20:52,800 --> 00:20:53,900
- Sorry.
- Look out!

114
00:20:54,100 --> 00:20:55,300
Watch out, will you?

115
00:20:55,500 --> 00:20:56,900
- Excuse me.
- Sorry.

116
00:20:58,400 --> 00:20:59,700
Sorry.

117
00:21:01,200 --> 00:21:04,000
Great. Would you be careful?

118
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:08,300
- Jimmy.
- Mr. Clark! I mean, Kent! Mr. Kent!

119
00:21:08,500 --> 00:21:10,500
Welcome back! Oh, my God!

120
00:21:10,700 --> 00:21:14,300
Hey, come... Wait right there.
I'll be right back.

121
00:21:23,400 --> 00:21:26,700
Oh, hey, sorry, guys,
I'm still looking for a place to live...

122
00:21:26,800 --> 00:21:28,500
...if you know of anything reasonable.

123
00:21:28,700 --> 00:21:32,200
Behind you, Mr. Kent.
I made it myself. It's a cake.

124
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:35,400
Oh, it looks...

125
00:21:36,400 --> 00:21:37,600
...delicious.

126
00:21:37,800 --> 00:21:41,900
Olsen! Where are the photos
of that birthday-clown-massacre thing?

127
00:21:42,100 --> 00:21:44,500
I'm on it, chief. Hey, look who's back.

128
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:46,300
- Kent?
- Hey, chief.

129
00:21:46,400 --> 00:21:48,800
- Thank you for giving me my job back.
- Don't thank me.

130
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:50,300
Thank Norm Palmer for dying.

131
00:21:52,100 --> 00:21:54,000
It was his time.

132
00:21:55,200 --> 00:21:58,600
- Let's get you set up, huh?
- Olsen!

133
00:21:58,800 --> 00:22:00,000
Okay, so I gotta run...

134
00:22:00,200 --> 00:22:03,300
...but I will be back to check on you
in a sec, Mr. Kent.

135
00:22:03,500 --> 00:22:07,500
Oh, hey, do you know
where I can find Lois?

136
00:22:20,800 --> 00:22:23,100
The timing of this
automated-ignition countdown...

137
00:22:23,300 --> 00:22:25,300
...is the most precarious part
of the launch.

138
00:22:25,800 --> 00:22:27,100
Lois Lane, Daily Planet.

139
00:22:27,200 --> 00:22:30,400
You also stated that the shuttle
will usher in a new era of travel...

140
00:22:30,500 --> 00:22:33,400
...enabling the average person
to afford transcontinental flights.

141
00:22:33,600 --> 00:22:35,600
But can you tell us the exact price...

142
00:22:35,800 --> 00:22:38,200
...an "average person"
will be expected to pay?

143
00:22:38,400 --> 00:22:41,000
The answer to that question
is in your press packet.

144
00:22:41,200 --> 00:22:43,800
The Earth is surrounded
by a blanket of air...

145
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:46,200
...which we call the atmosphere.

146
00:22:46,400 --> 00:22:49,800
It reaches over...

147
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:36,700
Yeah. He looks just like his mom.

148
00:23:36,800 --> 00:23:40,700
Already takes after her too, especially
when it comes to getting into trouble.

149
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:42,300
Mother?

150
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:48,500
Oh, yeah, well, I guess you've been gone.
Fearless reporter Lois Lane is a mommy.

151
00:23:50,800 --> 00:23:53,900
Oh, you know, I'll just...
I'll take that. That's good.

152
00:23:54,100 --> 00:23:56,900
- Sorry.
- No. She's got plenty.

153
00:23:57,000 --> 00:23:58,900
- Wait, she's married?
- Yes.

154
00:23:59,400 --> 00:24:03,300
No. Not really. It's more like
a prolonged engagement.

155
00:24:03,400 --> 00:24:05,800
But don't ask Miss Lane
when they're tying the knot...

156
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:09,300
...because she hates that question.

157
00:24:09,500 --> 00:24:13,800
- like this follow the same stringent
safety guidelines set by NASA?

158
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:16,500
Since this is a joint venture
with the Air Force...

159
00:24:16,600 --> 00:24:20,000
You all right? You look like
you could use a drink.

160
00:24:22,300 --> 00:24:25,400
This place is so tacky.
Why are we back here?

161
00:24:25,600 --> 00:24:29,100
Kitty, while you were doing your nails
and ordering fur coats online...

162
00:24:29,200 --> 00:24:30,900
...I was busy unlocking the secrets...

163
00:24:31,100 --> 00:24:33,800
...of one of the most advanced
civilizations in the universe.

164
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:35,200
Weren't there two of those?

165
00:24:35,400 --> 00:24:39,400
You see, unlike our clunky
earthbound forms of construction...

166
00:24:39,600 --> 00:24:41,900
...the technology on Krypton,
Superman's home world...

167
00:24:42,100 --> 00:24:44,400
...was based on manipulating
the growth of crystals.

168
00:24:44,600 --> 00:24:45,900
Sounds like hocus-pocus to me.

169
00:24:46,100 --> 00:24:49,700
Well, naturally, to the primitive mind,
any sufficiently advanced technology...

170
00:24:49,800 --> 00:24:51,900
...would be indistinguishable from magic.

171
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:56,200
But imagine: cities, vehicles, weapons...

172
00:24:56,800 --> 00:24:58,400
...entire continents...

173
00:24:58,700 --> 00:25:01,300
...all grown.

174
00:25:08,700 --> 00:25:11,900
To think that one could create
a new world...

175
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:14,900
...with such a simple little object.

176
00:25:16,600 --> 00:25:18,700
It's like a seed.

177
00:25:18,900 --> 00:25:21,100
And all it needs is water.

178
00:25:21,200 --> 00:25:22,600
Like...

179
00:25:23,400 --> 00:25:25,300
...Sea-Monkeys.

180
00:25:26,900 --> 00:25:29,100
Exactly, Kitty.

181
00:25:29,600 --> 00:25:31,200
Like Sea-Monkeys.

182
00:25:33,400 --> 00:25:37,700
Clark has been doing a little
soul-searching for the last couple years.

183
00:25:37,900 --> 00:25:39,800
- He saw Ilamas.
- Yeah?

184
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:41,900
- Yeah.
- Must be tough coming back.

185
00:25:43,600 --> 00:25:45,700
- Coming back?
- To work.

186
00:25:46,600 --> 00:25:48,000
Yeah.

187
00:25:48,400 --> 00:25:50,800
Well, you know, things change.

188
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:52,900
I mean, of course things change...

189
00:25:53,100 --> 00:25:58,700
...but sometimes things that you didn't
think would change could change.

190
00:25:59,200 --> 00:26:00,700
Take Lois.

191
00:26:00,900 --> 00:26:04,700
A woman like her,
I never thought she'd settle down.

192
00:26:05,100 --> 00:26:08,600
You know, if you ask me...
Because she'll never tell you this...

193
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:13,500
...but if you ask me,
she's still in love with you-know-who.

194
00:26:21,500 --> 00:26:25,200
The original space shuttle
generated 7.5 million pounds of thrust...

195
00:26:25,400 --> 00:26:27,000
...just in the initial launch phase.

196
00:26:27,200 --> 00:26:31,700
But, by piggybacking
on this Boeing 777... Yes?

197
00:26:31,900 --> 00:26:33,800
If this launch is as pivotal as you claim...

198
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:36,200
...why is it being covered
by one news network?

199
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:39,400
Why don't we save those questions
for the post-launch briefing.

200
00:26:39,600 --> 00:26:41,200
How about that, Miss Lane?

201
00:26:41,300 --> 00:26:44,600
When we hit 40,000 feet,
the shuttle will detach, ascend...

202
00:26:44,800 --> 00:26:48,300
...and then fire the first of two propellant
systems, the liquid fuel boosters.

203
00:26:48,500 --> 00:26:50,500
When the shuttle
reaches the stratosphere...

204
00:26:50,600 --> 00:26:52,700
...the secondary
insertion booster will fire...

205
00:26:52,800 --> 00:26:56,100
...propelling the craft
at 4gs into the mesosphere.

206
00:26:59,800 --> 00:27:01,800
- Careful.
- I know.

207
00:27:02,600 --> 00:27:05,500
- Careful. Careful.
- I know.

208
00:27:31,600 --> 00:27:34,000
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

209
00:27:34,200 --> 00:27:36,300
Wait for it.

210
00:27:39,600 --> 00:27:42,300
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

211
00:27:44,600 --> 00:27:47,200
It's freaking Gone With the Wind.

212
00:27:47,900 --> 00:27:49,800
- Shut off the camera.
- But I'm getting it.

213
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:51,900
I said, shut off the damn camera.

214
00:27:58,100 --> 00:27:59,700
I think I did something wrong.

215
00:27:59,900 --> 00:28:04,000
No. That wasn't you.

216
00:28:30,500 --> 00:28:34,000
Ignition is at T minus one minute
and we are prepping for separation.

217
00:28:34,200 --> 00:28:35,600
CDR., start the clock.

218
00:28:36,200 --> 00:28:38,400
Three minutes and counting.

219
00:28:38,600 --> 00:28:40,700
Body signs normal. Crew is looking good.

220
00:28:40,900 --> 00:28:42,500
Shuttle readouts are holding steady.

221
00:28:42,700 --> 00:28:44,800
- We're still a go for launch.
- Roger.

222
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:54,800
- Houston, you copy?
- Houston, do you copy?

223
00:28:58,600 --> 00:28:59,600
Oh, God.

224
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:02,700
Electrical variance.

225
00:29:06,300 --> 00:29:07,800
What the...?

226
00:29:14,400 --> 00:29:16,300
Please, there's nothing to worry about.

227
00:29:16,500 --> 00:29:20,600
It seems that we are experiencing
a slight power outage.

228
00:29:24,400 --> 00:29:27,700
- What did you do?
- It wasn't me. It just cycled back up.

229
00:29:29,200 --> 00:29:30,800
Genesis, radio check from Houston.

230
00:29:32,400 --> 00:29:34,700
There we have it.
We were experiencing a power outage.

231
00:29:37,100 --> 00:29:39,500
- Climbing to 40,000 feet.
- Roger, 40,000 feet.

232
00:29:50,600 --> 00:29:53,200
And it's gone! A blazing fastball...

233
00:30:13,800 --> 00:30:14,900
Is that it?

234
00:30:20,900 --> 00:30:23,100
I don't think so.

235
00:31:10,600 --> 00:31:12,900
Dual engine failure,
but they're up and running again.

236
00:31:13,100 --> 00:31:16,800
Genesis, I hate to say this, but it looks
like we're gonna have to scrub the launch.

237
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:20,300
- Aborting booster ignition.
- Roger. Aborting booster ignition.

238
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:25,100
Boosters are non-responsive.
We're still counting down for ignition.

239
00:31:25,300 --> 00:31:26,900
- Platform, we have a problem.
- Go.

240
00:31:27,100 --> 00:31:29,400
Looks like something faulted
during the power outage.

241
00:31:29,600 --> 00:31:31,800
Both boosters are
counting down for ignition.

242
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:33,800
Platform, you have 30 seconds.

243
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:35,200
- What?
- Release couplings.

244
00:31:35,400 --> 00:31:36,700
We can't shut down boosters.

245
00:31:36,800 --> 00:31:40,100
We should be able to manage the launch
and recover to the emergency field.

246
00:31:40,300 --> 00:31:41,800
T minus 23 seconds to ignition.

247
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:44,300
Genesis, you're a go
for evac procedures.

248
00:31:44,400 --> 00:31:47,200
Twenty-one, 20...

249
00:31:47,300 --> 00:31:48,800
...19...

250
00:31:51,800 --> 00:31:53,300
Couplings are non-responsive.

251
00:31:53,500 --> 00:31:55,300
- We're still attached.
- Seventeen.

252
00:31:56,400 --> 00:31:59,300
- Platform, couplings are jammed.
- Fifteen.

253
00:31:59,400 --> 00:32:01,200
