- Yeah? Name one.

498
01:00:33,500 --> 01:00:35,900
Well, there was a museum robbery
last night.

499
01:00:36,400 --> 01:00:39,700
Even Superman missed that one.
He was too busy saving this hooker.

500
01:00:39,900 --> 01:00:42,500
Why don't you guys
track down Lex Luthor?

501
01:00:43,200 --> 01:00:45,300
Well, no one's seen him
since his fifth appeal.

502
01:00:45,500 --> 01:00:47,500
He's got more history
with Superman than anyone.

503
01:00:47,700 --> 01:00:49,100
Maybe he's got something to say.

504
01:00:49,300 --> 01:00:52,900
- Luthor's yesterday's news.
- No, I like that idea.

505
01:00:53,800 --> 01:00:58,200
Perry, Lex Luthor is a career criminal
who nearly killed him, for God's sakes.

506
01:00:58,400 --> 01:01:00,500
Jimmy, how did Lex Luthor
get out of prison?

507
01:01:00,700 --> 01:01:04,500
Well, the appeals court called Superman
as a witness and he wasn't around.

508
01:01:05,200 --> 01:01:07,200
How much do you think
that pisses off Superman?

509
01:01:07,400 --> 01:01:09,000
- Give him to someone else.
- A lot.

510
01:01:09,100 --> 01:01:10,900
- A lot.
- Polly. Give him to Polly.

511
01:01:15,900 --> 01:01:17,400
Lois, Superman.

512
01:01:17,500 --> 01:01:19,600
- What about the blackout?
- Kent, blackout.

513
01:01:22,100 --> 01:01:24,300
Great. Thanks, chief.

514
01:01:27,400 --> 01:01:32,000
Lois, I'm sorry. I'd hate if this
damaged our relationship.

515
01:01:33,300 --> 01:01:34,300
Relationship?

516
01:01:35,100 --> 01:01:36,400
- Yeah.
- Hi, Mommy.

517
01:01:36,600 --> 01:01:38,400
- Hi, you.
- Hey, guys.

518
01:01:38,600 --> 01:01:42,200
He got an A in science, but a D in gym,
so we're doing something right.

519
01:01:42,400 --> 01:01:44,300
- Yeah, at least one of us is.
- What?

520
01:01:44,400 --> 01:01:47,200
It's Perry. He just shoved Superman
back into my life.

521
01:01:47,300 --> 01:01:50,100
Well, honey, I'm sure you can
find a way to interview Superman...

522
01:01:50,300 --> 01:01:52,200
...without bringing him
back into your life.

523
01:01:52,400 --> 01:01:56,500
There's really no way around it, folks.
Superman is back in all of our lives.

524
01:01:57,900 --> 01:01:59,600
We're coming to you from Sydney...

525
01:01:59,800 --> 01:02:03,400
...where people have gathered
on these rooftops to scour the sky...

526
01:02:03,600 --> 01:02:06,700
Okay, how about this?
We'll stay late. We'll get dinner.

527
01:02:06,800 --> 01:02:10,300
I'll help with Superman, and you and
Clark can work on the blackout together.

528
01:02:10,500 --> 01:02:13,300
- Is that all right with you, Clark?
- Swell.

529
01:02:36,200 --> 01:02:40,100
I was gonna pretend
the brakes were out.

530
01:02:40,300 --> 01:02:43,300
Pretend. Like we talked about.

531
01:02:43,400 --> 01:02:46,100
You didn't actually have to cut them!

532
01:02:46,300 --> 01:02:47,500
Of course I did.

533
01:02:47,700 --> 01:02:52,300
A man can always tell when a woman
is pretending, especially Superman.

534
01:02:57,000 --> 01:02:59,300
So did you get your rock?

535
01:03:00,600 --> 01:03:02,400
I did.

536
01:03:03,800 --> 01:03:07,600
U.S. Coast Guard issuing a small-craft
advisory for the Metropolis ocean area.

537
01:03:07,800 --> 01:03:09,500
High-wind advisory is in effect...

538
01:03:09,700 --> 01:03:12,500
...ocean currents and tides
becoming increasingly dangerous.

539
01:03:12,600 --> 01:03:15,700
All warnings lasting
until later this evening.

540
01:03:15,900 --> 01:03:17,100
Security, security.

541
01:03:17,200 --> 01:03:22,500
This is U.S. Coast Guard issuing
a small-craft advisory for northeast seas.

542
01:03:22,600 --> 01:03:26,900
Winds reaching 50 miles per hour,
high tides in the morning.

543
01:03:27,100 --> 01:03:28,800
Waves reaching 20 to 30 feet.

544
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:32,800
This warning is in effect for
all small crafts for the next four hours.

545
01:03:56,000 --> 01:03:57,500
Weird. If these times are right...

546
01:03:57,700 --> 01:04:00,600
...the blackout spread
from a specific origin point.

547
01:04:00,800 --> 01:04:02,100
Where?

548
01:04:02,300 --> 01:04:04,000
I'm not sure yet.

549
01:04:04,700 --> 01:04:08,200
With the super-hearing, does he hear each
sound by itself or everything at once?

550
01:04:08,600 --> 01:04:09,700
Both.

551
01:04:09,900 --> 01:04:12,000
- He's certainly taller than I thought.
- 6'4".

552
01:04:12,200 --> 01:04:15,800
I love that he can see through anything.
I'd have fun with that.

553
01:04:16,200 --> 01:04:17,800
Anything but lead.

554
01:04:20,900 --> 01:04:22,100
- I bet he's...
- 225 pounds...

555
01:04:22,300 --> 01:04:23,900
...faster than a speeding bullet...

556
01:04:24,000 --> 01:04:27,300
...draws his power from the sun,
invulnerable to anything but kryptonite...

557
01:04:27,500 --> 01:04:29,500
...and he never lies.
- Kryptonite?

558
01:04:29,600 --> 01:04:31,900
Radioactive pieces of his home world.

559
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:34,100
It's deadly. To him.

560
01:04:38,600 --> 01:04:41,800
Lois, how tall would you say Clark is?

561
01:04:43,300 --> 01:04:45,200
About 6'3", 6'4".

562
01:04:45,400 --> 01:04:48,000
About 200, 215 pounds?

563
01:04:57,600 --> 01:05:01,400
Jimmy, Jason, let's go get these intrepid
reporters something to keep them going.

564
01:05:01,600 --> 01:05:03,400
- Burritos!
- Come here, canhead.

565
01:05:04,800 --> 01:05:08,600
We're going this way. Do they have
anything other than burritos?

566
01:05:09,500 --> 01:05:11,700
I think they have fries and burgers.

567
01:05:11,900 --> 01:05:14,300
So have you found a place to live yet?

568
01:05:14,400 --> 01:05:15,900
No. I'm still looking.

569
01:05:16,700 --> 01:05:19,100
You know, Lois, I wanted to ask you
about that artic...

570
01:05:19,200 --> 01:05:22,600
Hey, I'm gonna run downstairs
for some fresh air. Great!

571
01:05:35,800 --> 01:05:37,400
Thanks.

572
01:05:44,900 --> 01:05:47,600
- Let's talk when I get back.
- Sure.

573
01:06:38,900 --> 01:06:41,500
You know, you really
shouldn't smoke, Miss Lane.

574
01:06:44,700 --> 01:06:47,100
- Sorry. Didn't mean to startle you.
- I'm fine. Really.

575
01:06:49,100 --> 01:06:52,100
I just wasn't expecting you.

576
01:06:52,800 --> 01:06:54,300
With all the press on the plane...

577
01:06:54,400 --> 01:06:56,700
...I wasn't sure it was
the best time for us to talk.

578
01:06:56,900 --> 01:07:00,000
Well, there's no press around now.
Except for me, of course.

579
01:07:02,100 --> 01:07:04,400
I know people are asking questions
now that I'm back.

580
01:07:04,800 --> 01:07:08,200
I think it's only fair
that I answer those people.

581
01:07:09,800 --> 01:07:13,000
So you're here for an interview?

582
01:07:14,200 --> 01:07:15,200
Okay, then.

583
01:07:18,900 --> 01:07:20,800
- Where did I put that thing?
- Right pocket.

584
01:07:26,700 --> 01:07:29,300
Let's start with the big question.

585
01:07:29,500 --> 01:07:31,900
- Where'd you go?
- To Krypton.

586
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:34,300
But you told me it was destroyed.
Ages ago.

587
01:07:34,500 --> 01:07:35,900
It was.

588
01:07:36,000 --> 01:07:38,300
But when astronomers
thought they found it...

589
01:07:39,700 --> 01:07:42,000
...I had to see for myself.

590
01:07:45,500 --> 01:07:49,100
Well, you're back, and everyone
seems to be pretty happy about it.

591
01:07:52,200 --> 01:07:53,600
Not everyone.

592
01:07:54,800 --> 01:07:57,100
- I read the article, Lois.
- So did a lot of people.

593
01:07:57,200 --> 01:08:00,100
- Tomorrow they're giving me the Pulitzer...
- Why did you write it?

594
01:08:01,700 --> 01:08:03,600
How could you leave us like that?

595
01:08:05,100 --> 01:08:07,400
I moved on. So did the rest of us.

596
01:08:07,900 --> 01:08:09,300
That's why I wrote it.

597
01:08:09,500 --> 01:08:12,100
The world doesn't need a savior.

598
01:08:12,600 --> 01:08:14,400
And neither do I.

599
01:08:28,900 --> 01:08:29,900
Lois.

600
01:08:31,600 --> 01:08:33,900
Will you come with me?

601
01:08:35,600 --> 01:08:37,100
Why?

602
01:08:37,500 --> 01:08:39,500
There's something I wanna show you.

603
01:08:45,600 --> 01:08:47,300
Please.

604
01:08:57,800 --> 01:08:59,900
I can't be gone long.

605
01:09:00,100 --> 01:09:01,900
You won't be.

606
01:09:13,800 --> 01:09:16,400
Clark said the reason you left
without saying goodbye...

607
01:09:16,600 --> 01:09:18,800
...is because it was
too unbearable for you.

608
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:21,500
Personally, I think that's a load of crap.

609
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:25,100
- Clark?
- He's just a guy I work with.

610
01:09:26,100 --> 01:09:28,100
Maybe Clark's right.

611
01:09:31,400 --> 01:09:33,400
You know, my...

612
01:09:33,600 --> 01:09:38,400
Richard, he's a pilot.
He takes me up all the time.

613
01:09:39,600 --> 01:09:41,500
Not like this.

614
01:09:55,700 --> 01:09:58,000
I forgot how warm you were.

615
01:10:27,400 --> 01:10:28,800
Listen.

616
01:10:29,700 --> 01:10:31,500
What do you hear?

617
01:10:32,200 --> 01:10:33,400
Nothing.

618
01:10:37,200 --> 01:10:38,800
I hear everything.

619
01:10:42,200 --> 01:10:44,700
You wrote that the world
doesn't need a savior...

620
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:49,200
...but every day
I hear people crying for one.

621
01:11:01,500 --> 01:11:04,000
I'm sorry I left you, Lois.

622
01:11:07,800 --> 01:11:09,700
I'll take you back now.

623
01:13:17,400 --> 01:13:19,000
Richard's a good man.

624
01:13:22,200 --> 01:13:24,300
And you've been gone a long time.

625
01:13:26,900 --> 01:13:28,400
I know.

626
01:13:33,000 --> 01:13:34,300
I...

627
01:13:39,300 --> 01:13:41,200
So will I see you around?

628
01:13:42,200 --> 01:13:44,100
I'm always around.

629
01:13:45,300 --> 01:13:47,000
Good night, Lois.

630
01:14:05,200 --> 01:14:08,900
We're having beef, honey. Do you want
the tofu wrap or the veggie wrap?

631
01:14:12,600 --> 01:14:14,100
You all right?

632
01:14:15,900 --> 01:14:17,300
Where have you been?

633
01:14:21,900 --> 01:14:26,100
I was up on the roof, getting some air.

634
01:14:27,100 --> 01:14:29,000
Tell the truth now.

635
01:14:35,300 --> 01:14:36,400
Were you smoking?

636
01:14:38,900 --> 01:14:40,600
No.

637
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:50,200
Is this real?

638
01:14:51,200 --> 01:14:53,000
- Where'd you find him?
- He found me.

639
01:14:53,100 --> 01:14:55,800
Oh, this is great. I can't wait to read it.

640
01:14:56,000 --> 01:14:58,300
So, Mr. White, about the blackout...

641
01:14:58,500 --> 01:15:00,900
Lois, this is the biggest night
of your life.

642
01:15:01,000 --> 01:15:03,100
Have you picked out a dress?
Something snazzy?

643
01:15:04,100 --> 01:15:06,700
It just feels a little weird
winning for that article.

644
01:15:06,800 --> 01:15:09,700
- It just doesn't seem right.
- What doesn't seem right?

645
01:15:09,900 --> 01:15:13,300
Winning an award for an article called
"Why the World Doesn't Need Superman."

646
01:15:13,500 --> 01:15:15,900
When, according
to this newspaper, they do.

647
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:18,800
Lois, Pulitzer Prizes
are like Academy Awards.

648
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:22,000
Nobody remembers what you got one for.
It's just that you got one.

649
01:15:22,100 --> 01:15:25,100
- But...
- This is your night. You enjoy it.

650
01:15:25,300 --> 01:15:27,700
I'm sure Kent's on the blackout.

651
01:16:25,800 --> 01:16:27,900
Department of Water and Power, please.

652
01:16:28,600 --> 01:16:29,900
7782, great.

653
01:16:31,300 --> 01:16:32,700
Metropolis Public Works.

654
01:16:32,900 --> 01:16:35,300
Hi, Stephen, Lois Lane
from the Daily Planet. Blackout?

655
01:16:35,400 --> 01:16:38,000
I just need a little info
on a few outstanding power grids.

656
01:16:38,200 --> 01:16:39,700
Yeah, I do have it here, actually.

657
01:16:39,900 --> 01:16:43,700
So the uptown grid went dark at 12:36
and midtown 10 seconds before.

658
01:16:43,900 --> 01:16:45,300
Which grid was hit first?

659
01:16:45,500 --> 01:16:46,800
It just reads Vanderworth.

660
01:16:46,900 --> 01:16:49,200
- Across the river?
- 6 Springwood Drive.

661
01:16:49,400 --> 01:16:51,500
6 Springwood Drive.
A residence or a business?

662
01:16:51,700 --> 01:16:53,400
- Residence.
- Sure? Nothing before that?

663
01:16:53,500 --> 01:16:55,800
- That's all it shows.
- Thank you very much.

664
01:16:57,500 --> 01:16:58,800
Oh, Jason.

665
01:17:05,300 --> 01:17:08,400
- There's your mom, Jason.
- You're late, Mommy.

